  "text": "Training methodologies that combine low intensity aerobic exercise in situations that mimic the reduction of tissue nutrients present in patients with T1D, such as venous occlusion training techniques, have been shown to result in significant metabolic adaptations associated with improvements in insulin sensitivity and muscle strength [CITATION_1] . Moreover, despite the proposition that high intensity interval training can promote increases in the capillary density of skeletal muscle, this exercise intensity has recently been suggested to be small compared to lower exercise intensities [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
